{"cursor":"12587","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nA 'widow' is a woman whose spouse has\ndied, while a 'widower' is a man whose spouse has died. The\nstate of having lost one's spouse to death is termed widowhood. This term can be\nused for either sex, at least according to some dictionaries, [http://www.c-\nollinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/widowhood \"Widowhood\" as defined by Col-\nlins] [http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/widowhood?vie-\nw=uk \"Widowhood\" as defined by Oxford] but the word widowerhood is also\nlisted in some dictionaries. [http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/e-\nnglish/widowerhood \"Widowerhood\" as defined by Collins] [http://www.merriam-\nwebster.com/dictionary/widowerhood \"Widowerhood\" as defined by Merriam-\nWebster's] Occasionally, the word viduity is used. The adjective form for\neither sex [http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/widowed\n\"Widowed\" as defined by\nCollins] [http://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/british/widowed\n\"Widowed\" as defined by Cambridge] is widowed. The treatment of widows\naround the world varies, but unequal benefits and treatment generally received\nby widows versus widowers globally has spurred an interest in the issue by human\nrights activists. Owen, Margaret. A World of Widows.\nIllustrated. Atlantic Highlands, NJ: Zed Books, 1996. 181-183. eBook.\n","linknr":323,"url":"Widow","recorded":1374966588,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Widow&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Widow&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%